Honest ExecutionTarget::Gpu: fail load() when the CUDA execution provider
cannot initialize, instead of ORT's default silent CPU fallback.

Why (NAN): a tenant that bought a GPU share and asked for ::Gpu must get the
card or an error — never a quiet downgrade to CPU that still looks like a
successful GPU inference. Silent fallback would also make the demo/verification
app lie on GPU-less nodes. Applied to the wasmtime source by
Dockerfile.wasmtime before building the toolchain image.

diff --git a/crates/wasi-nn/src/backend/onnx.rs b/crates/wasi-nn/src/backend/onnx.rs
index c7cc645..b70dc93 100644
--- a/crates/wasi-nn/src/backend/onnx.rs
+++ b/crates/wasi-nn/src/backend/onnx.rs
@@ -67,9 +67,12 @@ fn configure_execution_providers(
         ExecutionTarget::Gpu => {
             #[cfg(feature = "onnx-cuda")]
             {
-                // Use CUDA execution provider for GPU acceleration
+                // Use CUDA execution provider for GPU acceleration. NAN: fail
+                // the load if the provider can't initialize — ORT's default is
+                // a SILENT fallback to CPU, which would let a "GPU" inference
+                // quietly run on the CPU.
                 tracing::debug!("Using Nvidia GPU CUDA execution provider");
-                Ok(vec![CUDAExecutionProvider::default().build()])
+                Ok(vec![CUDAExecutionProvider::default().build().error_on_failure()])
             }
             #[cfg(not(feature = "onnx-cuda"))]
             {
